[h1]The for loop[/h1]

A [b]for [/b]loop is a repetition control structure that allows you to efficiently write a loop that executes a specific number of times.
[b]Syntax:[/b] [code format="cpp"][b]for [/b]( [b]init[/b]; [b]condition[/b]; [b]increment [/b]) {
  statement(s);
}[/code]
The [b]init [/b]step is executed first, and does not repeat.
Next, the [b]condition [/b]is evaluated, and the body of the loop is executed if the condition is true.
In the next step, the [b]increment [/b]statement updates the loop control variable.
Then, the loop's body repeats itself, only stopping when the condition becomes [b]false[/b].

For example:[code format="cpp"][b]for [/b](int x = 1; x < 10; x++) {
 // some code
 }[/code]
[note]The [b]init [/b]and [b]increment [/b]statements may be left out, if not needed, but remember that the [b]semicolons [/b]are mandatory.[/note]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to print x's values to the screen 10 times:
[!raw!]
{0} (int x = 1; x <= 10; {1}++) {
  cout << x << endl;
}

Fill in the blanks to print EVEN (multiples of 2) values from 0 to 20 using a for loop:
[!raw!]
for (int x = 0{0} x <= {1} x += {2}) {
  cout << {3} << endl;
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The for Loop [/h1]

It's possible to change the increment statement.[code format="cpp" codeId="204"]for (int a = 0; a < 50;[b] a+=10[/b]) {
  cout << a << endl;
}
/* Outputs
0
10
20
30
40
*/
[/code]
You can also use decrement in the statement.[code format="cpp" codeId="205"]for (int a = 10; a >= 0;[b] a -= 3[/b]) {
  cout << a << endl;
}

/* Outputs
10
7
4
1
*/[/code]
[note]When using the for loop, don't forget the [b]semicolon [/b]after the [b]init [/b]and [b]condition [/b]statements.[/note]
